<speak version="1.0" xml:lang="en-US" xmlns:mstts="http://www.w3.org/2001/mstts">
  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="-7%" pitch="+0st">
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S1"/> Welcome to our lesson on cells! Cells are the building blocks of life.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S3"/> They are essential for all living organisms. In this lesson, we will explore what a cell is, its importance, and the different types of cells.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S5"/> By the end, you will understand the basic functions of cells and how they differ from one another. So, what exactly is a cell?</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S7"/> A cell is the smallest unit of life. It can perform all the necessary functions to sustain life.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S9"/> Cells come in many shapes and sizes, but they all share some common features. let's talk about the two main types of cells: prokaryotic and eukaryotic.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S11"/> Prokaryotic cells are simple and do not have a nucleus. They are usually smaller and include bacteria.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S13"/> On the other hand, eukaryotic cells are more complex. They have a nucleus and organelles.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S15"/> Examples include plant and animal cells. Understanding these differences is crucial in biology.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S17"/> Each type of cell has unique functions and roles in living organisms. let's look at some basic functions of cells.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S19"/> Cells take in nutrients, convert them into energy, and eliminate waste. They also reproduce and respond to their environment.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S21"/> These functions are vital for survival. A common pitfall is thinking that all cells are the same.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S23"/> Remember, prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells have distinct characteristics. To check your understanding, can you name one key difference between prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells?</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S25"/> Great! Now let's recap what we've learned.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S27"/> Cells are the fundamental units of life. We differentiated between prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells and identified their basic functions.</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S29"/> Understanding cells is essential for studying biology. Thank you for joining this lesson!</p>
<break time="500ms"/>
    </prosody>
  </voice></speak>